{"cursor":"12053","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\n\n\nA 'centrifuge' is a piece of equipment, generally driven by an electric motor\n(some older models were spun by hand), that puts an object in rotation around a\nfixed axis, applying a force perpendicular to the axis. The centrifuge works\nusing the sedimentation principle, where the centripetal acceleration causes\ndenser substances to separate out along the radial direction (the bottom of the\ntube). By the same token lighter objects will tend to move to the top (of the\ntube; in the rotating picture, move to the centre).\n","linknr":281,"url":"Centrifuge","recorded":1362552465,"links":57,"instances":["milk","physics"],"pdf":["http://www.thermo.com/eThermo/CMA/PDFs/Various/File_6810.pdf","http://uqu.edu.sa/files2/tiny_mce/plugins/filemanager/files/4250119/lectures/1._instr.pdf","http://www.civil.ubc.ca/liquefaction/Publications/flow%20liq_Naesgaard%20et%20al%20version31.pdf"],"categories":["Centrifuges|Centrifuges"],"headings":["Theory","History and predecessors","Types","Uses","References and notes","Further reading","See also","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/50px-Question_book-new.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0d/Tabletop_centrifuge.jpg/200px-Tabletop_centrifuge.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/4/d/1/4d1b7b74aba3cfabd624e898d86b4602.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/86/19thCentrifuge.JPG/200px-19thCentrifuge.JPG","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/6/3/8/638390d87a7bda4a53b7f732d603b9a6.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/c/1/7/c172541f77a147fcf545237fefa03643.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/8/3/0/83054bf551c8f66f3faca2d9d367a464.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/4/d/1/4d1b7b74aba3cfabd624e898d86b4602.png","//upload.wikimedia.or